
  <sn><md>### Determination of the Rate of Profit {.text-center}

**Example 5.** What is the rate of profit by which the profit of Tk. 3,000 will be Tk. 1,500 in 5 years?

**Solution:**

We know, $I = Prn$<br>
or, $r = \dfrac{I}{Pn}$ <br>
or, $r\% = \dfrac{I}{Pn}$ <br>
or, $\frac{r}{100} = \dfrac{I}{Pn}$ <br>
or, $r = \dfrac{I \times 100}{Pn}$



:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-8

Therefore, Rate of profit = $\dfrac{\text{Profit}}{\text{Principal} \times \text{Time}}$

* $= \dfrac{1,500}{3,000 \times 5}$

* $= \dfrac{1,500}{15,000}$

* $= \dfrac{1}{10} \%$

* $= \dfrac{1}{10} \times 100$

* $= 10\%$

∴ The rate of profit is **10%**.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-4
**Where,**
| Symbol | Value |
|--------|-------|
| $P$ | Principal = Tk. 3,000 |
| $I$ | Profit = Tk. 1,500 |
| $r$ | Rate of Profit = Required |
| $n$ | Time = 5 years |
:::
:::
</md></sn>
